WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.787
I was 13 and a half when I arrived in Auschwitz.&nbsp;
I was 14. Two weeks after my 13th birthday.

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:24.680
There was an announcement that we should go&nbsp;
to the train that was on the tracks. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:32.520
were rushing us, screaming, yelling go fast,&nbsp;
fast, hurry. My favorite teacher was shot on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:41.440
the step because she absolutely refused to&nbsp;
get on to the train. We tried very hard to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:47.200
stay together as a family and hold on to&nbsp;
each other. We did not have place to sit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:54.800
we were standing all along. On the second or third&nbsp;
day when people started dying in the car, that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.800 --> 00:01:04.760
was a relief. Dead bodies could be stacked like&nbsp;
cordwood and that created a little more space.

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:10.800
The doors opened and they started yelling,&nbsp;
get out, get out. There was the smell,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:19.840
this incredible, inhuman, otherworldly stench.&nbsp;
There was bedlam, because they were immediately&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:28.400
beginning to separate families. Two SS officers&nbsp;
were directing people right or left. We children&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:35.000
held each other's hands, we held our parents'&nbsp;
hands. I mean we're just literally torn apart&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:43.280
in a matter of minutes. I was separated from&nbsp;
my mother. I remember my dad going up that way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:49.800
I remember staying with my sister. I&nbsp;
had a younger sister, holding her hand,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.800 --> 00:02:00.280
stick came down between us and she was sent off. I&nbsp;
lost her, I lost my little sister somehow. Before&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.280 --> 00:02:12.160
we were taken to barracks we were processed.&nbsp;
Undressed, the hair cut, body hair cut. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:18.720
came out looking identical. Sisters, mothers&nbsp;
wouldn't identify each other. We were no longer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:27.360
people. You were thrown some ragged, used, filthy&nbsp;
striped uniforms. You were tossed some shoes with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:40.160
wooden soles. Then you get into the barracks and&nbsp;
then life starts. And life was learning to die.

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:47.480
When we entered the barrack, minutes after we got&nbsp;
in, a young woman was running towards my sister.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.480 --> 00:02:55.520
She told us right away: I want you to know that&nbsp;
your mother and your siblings are already dead.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.520 --> 00:03:03.120
And that was also a shock, but an unbelievable&nbsp;
one. I remember rejecting it completely. I just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:11.560
felt terrified the whole time I was there, so&nbsp;
scared because they were looking at us like we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:18.200
were subhumans, they treated us like subhumans.&nbsp;
They had all the power and we were nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:26.920
we were just… That was the intent. Yes. One after&nbsp;
the other my classmates were dying of hunger,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:39.560
exhaustion, and just total mental and&nbsp;
physical collapse. I was the last one.

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:49.720
We were next to a gas chamber and crematorium&nbsp;
with just an electrified fence. We saw the huge&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.880 --> 00:04:00.160
numbers of people walking from the train&nbsp;
past our barrack into the gas chamber.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:05.840
And often they talked to us. They’d call out:&nbsp;
where are you from, and what's your name,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:05.840 --> 00:04:13.880
and do you know so and so. Minutes later&nbsp;
the chimneys were belching fire so hard&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:22.520
that it was like a roaring sound. It&nbsp;
was just unbelievable. It wasn't smoke,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.520 --> 00:04:30.040
it was flames like you know, like a wind, and we&nbsp;
had just seen them. We had just talked to them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:38.000
Little children carried by their mothers, pregnant&nbsp;
women, and we can't tell them that they have a few&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:49.120
minutes to live. My memory of Auschwitz is the&nbsp;
actual extermination, and anything else that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:59.640
was good or bad cannot be compared. It was a&nbsp;
universe of its own, it was below the human&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:09.120
understanding, tolerance, ability to absorb.&nbsp;
It's constantly with me. I just can't believe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:16.440
it that people can deny something that&nbsp;
was so right there in front of their eyes.

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:29.640
My story, coming from my mouth, cannot be denied.

